            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers standing on a curb in SoMa in 2001, watching movers haul ergonomic chairs out of a defunct startup\u2019s office. They left a bright orange foosball table behind, a monument to failed optimism. He felt no joy, only a cold, clarifying calm. In the wreckage of ephemeral ideas, the real estate\u2014the physical space itself\u2014was all that remained. That moment wasn't about a market crash; it was the day his professional creed was forged in concrete and steel. It taught him to trust only what he could touch.\n\n2.\nThe phone felt hot against his ear in 2008 as he closed the deal that would make his career. He hung up, adrenaline singing in his veins, and turned to tell his wife. She was standing in the bedroom doorway, holding two suitcases. His triumphant smile faltered and died. The greatest professional victory of his life was instantly eclipsed by his most devastating personal loss. He learned then that the price of building an empire could be the kingdom of his own home.\n\n3.\nVikram sat beside his daughter in a Stanford caf\u00e9 a few years ago as she explained the significance of an obscure Renaissance fresco. He didn't understand the art history, but he understood the fierce, quiet passion in her eyes. It was the same fire he felt when analyzing a balance sheet. In her academic world, so much like the one he\u2019d fled, he saw a reflection of his own relentless drive. A painful, beautiful irony that filled him with a sudden, aching pride.\n\n4.\nHe must have been ten, tagging along on a trip to the city with his father. While his dad disappeared into a Berkeley building for a seminar, Vikram stood mesmerized by a construction site across the street. He watched a crane hoist a massive steel I-beam, slotting it perfectly into the growing skeleton of a skyscraper. It felt more real and important than any book he\u2019d ever read. It was the first time he understood that some legacies aren\u2019t written, but built.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on his morning walk down California Street, he stopped. He\u2019d sold the building on the corner twice, but he\u2019d never truly seen it. He noticed the intricate terra-cotta detailing below the seventh-floor window, catching the morning sun. For a fleeting moment, the building wasn't an asset or a number; it was a piece of the city's soul he had cared for. It felt like a different kind of ownership, one that didn't come with a deed."
